                </p>
                <p>
                    The main thing to know about CSS animations is that your CSS
                    styles (font size, color, position, width, height, etc.) can
                    vary and the change may be animated. You define Keyframes
                    which are the turning points of your animation and the
                    transition between these stages creates motion. For example,
                    three different colors that your element passes through, or
                    two positions it should traverse.
                </p>
            </Article>
        </div>
        <div class="">
            <Article>
                <p>
                    Once you have the keyframes the transition needs a duration
                    in which the stages are reeled off. Additionally, the
                    animation may be given a delay, a direction, an
                    iteration/repetition, and a timing function.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Have a look at the options at <a
                        href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/css3_animations.asp"
                        >w3schools</a
                    >. For instance, check out <a
                        href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/css3_2dtransforms.asp"
                        >2D</a
                    > and <a
                        href="https://www.w3schools.com/css/css3_3dtransforms.asp"
